# RedMed — project rules for AI coding assistants

Local-first emergency medical ID app. Owner fills in profile data once;
it's written to a **passive** NFC chip (wristband/tag); a smartphone that
taps energizes the chip and reads the data. No backend, no accounts, nothing
ever sent to a server, by design — keep it that way unless explicitly told
to change it.

**Passive NFC only:** NTAG-style ISO 14443 tags — no BLE beacons, no active
RFID, no battery-powered bands, no continuous broadcast. Do not add radio
features beyond phone-tap read/write of NDEF URI records.

## Sole repository

This product lives in **one** GitHub repo only:
`https://github.com/MaxRoot1122/RedMed`.

Do not create, recommend, or depend on a second repo (including a
`MaxRoot1122.github.io` user-site, a fork used as the "real" source, or
a multi-repo Cursor environment). Hosting, Android TWA, iOS, docs, and
agent work all stay inside this repo. Canonical public host (live) is
`https://maxroot1122.github.io/RedMed/` (NFC card = `/index.html`).
`www.redmed.com` is **not** live yet (parking lander) — keep it in
`config/CNAME.future` / `legacy:` until DNS → Pages is verified
(see `docs/DOMAIN.md`). Do not write new tags to www until then.

## Where things live

- `ios/RedMed/` — **primary owner app** (SwiftUI). Open **`ios/RedMed.xcodeproj`**
  in Xcode (NFC capability, `redmed://` URL scheme, bundle ID `local.redmed.app`
  are preconfigured — see `ios/SETUP.md`). Product UI edits for iPhone owners
  land here first. Nothing here has ever been compiled in this Linux cloud
  environment; treat any Swift edit as unverified until built on a real Mac.
- `index.html` — **NFC emergency card** + Android/web fallback. Single file,
  inline `<style>`/`<script>`, no build step. Bracelet taps open this hosted
  page with `#d=` profile data. Also carries owner tabs (My ID / Aid / 911) for
  Android TWA and browsers. Do **not** delete or replace with Swift — any-phone
  NFC requires a public HTTPS HTML card. Views toggle via `location.hash`.
- `android/` — a bare Trusted Web Activity (TWA) wrapper around a hosted
  copy of `index.html`. Zero native UI code exists — see `android/SETUP.md`
  for NFC write gap (iOS native; Android Chrome Web NFC on hosted page).
- `get.html` — store-routing QR landing (iOS / Samsung / Huawei / Play).
- `RedMed.app/` — macOS launcher: runs **`scripts/run-ios-simulator.sh`** (native iOS in Simulator). Not a web browser. Web mirror at `Contents/Resources/www/` is for hosted/NFC card only — sync with `./scripts/sync-www-mirror.sh` after `index.html` edits.
- `assets/icon.svg` — source of truth for the **app cover / home-screen icon**
  (bronze cross + red serpent on the rose plate). All PNG/ICNS variants are
  generated from this — regenerate after editing, don't hand-edit the rasters.
- `assets/wordmark.svg` — web hero wordmark; `assets/wordmark-ios.svg` — iOS
  `BrandWordmark` source. See `docs/BRAND.md` for which asset goes where.
- `assets/trauma-hospitals.{json,js}` — bundled offline trauma center
  directory for **Find 911** (see `docs/TRAUMA_FINDER.md`). Web loads
  `.js` via `<script src>`; iOS bundles `.json`. Keep copies in sync.
- `docs/TRAUMA_FINDER.md` — agent handoff for trauma center UX, schema,
  file list, and verification. Read before editing Find 911 trauma UI.

## Things that will silently break if you miss them

- **`index.html`'s CSP pins an exact `sha256-` hash of the inline
  `<script>` block.** Any edit inside `<script>...</script>` invalidates
  that hash — the whole page's JS silently stops running (CSP blocks it,
  no visible error in a static read, only in the browser console) until
  you recompute it: hash the exact script text (UTF-8, byte-for-byte) and
  update the `script-src` directive in the `<meta http-equiv="Content-
  Security-Policy">` tag. CSS-only edits don't affect this hash.
- **`RedMed.app/Contents/Resources/www/index.html` must stay byte-identical
  to root `index.html`.** It's a manual copy, not a symlink or build step —
  `cp index.html "RedMed.app/Contents/Resources/www/index.html"` after any
  web edit, then `diff` to confirm. Or run `./scripts/sync-www-mirror.sh`.
  Copy `assets/trauma-hospitals.*` into
  `RedMed.app/Contents/Resources/www/assets/` when trauma data changes.
- **Passive NFC only.** Bracelets are **passive NTAG** chips (ISO 14443 Type A,
  NDEF URI). No battery, no BLE beacon, no active RFID, no continuous
  broadcast — the phone powers the chip on tap. App code: CoreNFC + Web NFC
  write only; do not add Bluetooth, UHF, or live-tracking radios.
- **NFC opens on smartphones, on purpose.** `AppConfig.medicalCardBaseURL`
  points at the hosted root **`index.html`** (canonical today:
  `https://maxroot1122.github.io/RedMed/index.html`; sync via
  `config/canonical-url`). Tags store that URL plus `#d=` profile data
  on the bracelet chip — no account, no cloud sync. SwiftUI is the owner
  companion (write/read NFC, Face ID, Keychain); the emergency card UI is the
  hosted `index.html`, not an in-app WebView. A stranger's **smartphone** taps
  the band and the card opens in the phone browser (tablets/desktops see a gate
  screen). Keep `redmed://` registered only as a legacy deep-link; don't switch
  writes back to app-only without an explicit ask.
- **Never fake satellite-tracking/pointing UI.** No public API (iOS or
  Android) exposes real satellite position/connectivity data to
  third-party apps — Apple's Emergency SOS via satellite (Globalstar) and
  Android's Satellite SOS (Skylo) are both private OS-vendor integrations.
  A fake "point your phone here" indicator in a safety-critical app is a
  real harm vector if someone trusts it during an actual no-signal
  emergency. Real device compass heading (`CLLocationManager`) is fine and
  already implemented; simulated satellite direction is not.
- **No backend, no cloud sync of profile data.** Cloud sync was
  deliberately removed for a cleaner local-only / HIPAA-adjacent posture.
  Don't reintroduce network calls carrying profile data without explicit
  instruction. **Exception:** optional Google Maps Platform on Find 911 only
  (`connect-src https://maps.googleapis.com`) — see `docs/TRAUMA_FINDER.md`.

## Conventions

- Comments explain *why*, not *what* — keep that pattern.
- No unused CSS classes or dead views — check whether something is
  actually referenced before assuming it's load-bearing.
- Brace/paren-balance-check any Swift edit (`python3` one-liner counting
  `{`/`}` and `(`/`)`) since there's no Xcode here to catch syntax errors.
